Clustering (Part I)

Ryan Miller

Clustering

  • In unsupervised learning a possible goal might be to identify hidden groups within the data
    • Principle components analysis (PCA) intends to find hidden groups of variables (columns)
    • Clustering intends to find hidden groups of data-points (rows)

Clustering

  • The plot below provides an example of clustering, but how might we decide if Virginia belongs in Cluster #1 or Cluster #2?

Distance

  • Good clusters contain data-points that are similar (close to) eachother and dissimilar (far from) from data-points belonging to other clusters
  • To objectively measure “closeness” we need to use a distance metric, the simplest choice is Euclidean distance:

\[d_{a,b} = \sqrt{\sum_{j = 1}^{p} (x_{aj} - x_{bj})^2}\]

  • The distance between data-points \(x_a\) and \(x_b\) is the sum of the squared differences in their values across each variable (we index the variables using \(j \in \{1, \ldots, p\}\))

Distance Matrices

  • If we have \(n\) data-points, there are \(n-1\) possible distances of interest
  • We can summarize the distances between all \(n\) points using a distance matrix
  • By visualizing the distance matrix we can observe some trends in the data:
distance <- get_dist(USArrests[,c(1,3)])
fviz_dist(distance)

Standardization

  • Like PCA, we might not want to let certain variables with larger units dominate, so we might consider standardizing (re-scaling) the data before calculating distance
  • We can see the impact this has on the USArrests data:
distance <- get_dist(USArrests[,c(1,3)], stand = TRUE)
fviz_dist(distance)

Cluster Centers

  • Analyzing distances between data-points can be informative, but we need to go further to explicitly group the data into clusters
  • To do so, we compare the distance between data-points and a cluster center (sometimes called a centroid), let \(\mu_k\) be the center of the \(k^{th}\) cluster and \(x_i\) be a data-point in the \(k^{th}\) cluster

\[ \text{Total Withiness} = \sum_{k=1}^{k} W(C_k) = \sum_{k=1}^{k} \sum_{x_i \in C_k} (x_i - \mu_k)^2 \]

  • An optimal cluster assignment minimizes the Total Withiness (sometimes called the total within cluster sum of squares)

k-Means Clustering

  • k-means is a popular clustering algorithm where each cluster center (\(\mu_k\)) is defined to be that cluster’s mean (in \(p\)-dimensional space)
    • The algorithm requires the user specify a value for \(k\)
    • Next, \(k\) cluster centers are randomly generated and the data-points are grouped into clusters such that the total withiness (using these cluster centers) is minimized
    • Next, the cluster centers are updated to be mean of the data-points which belong to the cluster
    • Next, using the updated cluster centers, data-points are re-grouped to minimize total withiness
    • The cycle of re-grouping and determining new cluster centers continues until convergence

Visualizing k-Means

  • Often it is useful to combine clustering and principle components analysis to produce interpretable visuals
  • In this example, recall that Dimension 1 roughly represented overall crime, and Dimension 2 roughly represented urban population
    • We see that \(k\)-means (with \(k =2\)) groups states mostly in accordance their differences in crime
km <- kmeans(scale(USArrests), centers = 2)
fviz_cluster(km, data = scale(USArrests))

Standardization and k-Means

  • Standardization will influence your k-means clusters
    • If you have variables with incompatible units you should standardize

Increasing k

  • As we manipulate \(k\) we can see the clusters change primarily in Dimension 1
    • This is expected since the dimension contains the vast majority of variation in the data
km3 <- kmeans(scale(USArrests), centers = 3)
p1 <- fviz_cluster(km3, data = scale(USArrests)) + ggtitle("k = 3")

km4 <- kmeans(scale(USArrests), centers = 4)
p2 <- fviz_cluster(km4, data = scale(USArrests)) + ggtitle("k = 4")

gridExtra::grid.arrange(p1,p2)

Choosing k

  • There are dozens of proposed methods for choosing the number of clusters, we will discuss three of them:
    • The elbow method
    • The silhouette method
    • The gap statistic

The Elbow Method

  • The elbow method is simple and intuitive, it just plots “Total Withiness” or “wss” versus the number of clusters
    • While wss will always decrease with \(k\), eventually the decreases become small
    • So, we can find an “elbow” where the there isn’t much improvement when further increasing \(k\)
    • In the example below, we conclude that using 2-4 clusters would be reasonable
USArrests_scaled <- scale(USArrests)
fviz_nbclust(USArrests_scaled, kmeans, method = "wss", k.max = 8)

The Silhouette Method

  • The elbow method is somewhat subject, in contrast the silhouette method objectively calculates a silhouette value for each data-point
    • We won’t cover the details, but silhouette values range from +1 (a perfect match with the assigned cluster) and -1 (a poor match with the assigned cluster)
    • The average silhouette value can be used to determine the optimal \(k\)
    • In the USArrests example, the method suggests \(k = 2\) is optimal
fviz_nbclust(USArrests_scaled, kmeans, method = "silhouette", k.max = 8)

The Silhouette Method

  • Silhouettes are also useful to investigate how well individual data-points fit within their assigned cluster
k2 <- kmeans(USArrests_scaled, centers = 2, nstart = 25)
sil <- silhouette(k2$cluster, dist(USArrests_scaled), ordered = FALSE)
row.names(sil) <- row.names(USArrests) # Needed to use label option
fviz_silhouette(sil, label = TRUE)
##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1   20          0.37
## 2       2   30          0.43

The Gap Statistic

  • The “Total Withiness” always declines as \(k\) increases
  • The idea behind the gap statistic is to determine what amount of “Total Withiness” is explected for a given \(k\), and then look at the gap between the observed measure and this expected value.
    • More specific details can be found in the paper here
  • Larger gap statistics are desirable, as they indicate the clusters are doing better than what we’d expect
  • When using the gap statistic we should consider parsimony, by default fviz_nbclust will select the smallest \(k\) within one standard error of the maximum
fviz_nbclust(USArrests_scaled, kmeans, method = "gap", k.max = 8)
